{
  "Solve by substitution: x = 2y and x + y = 9.": "",
  "y = 6, x = 3": "",
  "y = 2, x = 9": "",
  "y = 3, x = 6": "",
  "y = 1, x = 2": "",
  "Substitute x = 2y into x + y = 9: 2y + y = 9, so 3y = 9 and y = 3. Then x = 2(3) = 6.": "",
  "From y = 3x - 1, substitute into 2x + y = 9. What equation results?": "",
  "2x + 3x + 1 = 9": "",
  "2x - 3x + 1 = 9": "",
  "2x(3x - 1) = 9": "",
  "2x + 3x - 1 = 9": "",
  "Replace y with (3x - 1) in the second equation: 2x + (3x - 1) = 9. This is a direct substitution — replace the variable, not multiply.": "",
  "Solve by substitution: y = x + 4 and 2x + y = 10.": "",
  "x = 1, y = 5": "",
  "x = 4, y = 8": "",
  "x = 2, y = 6": "",
  "x = 3, y = 7": "",
  "Substitute y = x + 4 into 2x + y = 10: 2x + (x + 4) = 10 → 3x + 4 = 10 → 3x = 6 → x = 2. Then y = 2 + 4 = 6.": "",
  "Solve: x = 5 - y and 3x + 2y = 12.": "",
  "x = 4, y = 1": "",
  "x = 2, y = 3": "",
  "x = 3, y = 2": "",
  "x = 1, y = 4": "",
  "Substitute x = 5 - y into 3x + 2y = 12: 3(5 - y) + 2y = 12 → 15 - 3y + 2y = 12 → -y = -3 → y = 3. Then x = 5 - 3 = 2.": "",
  "Solve: y = -2x + 7 and y = x + 1.": "",
  "x = 4, y = 5": "",
  "x = 3, y = 4": "",
  "Set -2x + 7 = x + 1: -3x = -6, so x = 2. Then y = 2 + 1 = 3.": "",
  "Solve: 2x + y = 8 and y = x - 1.": "",
  "x = 5, y = 4": "",
  "x = 4, y = 3": "",
  "x = 2, y = 1": "",
  "Substitute y = x - 1 into 2x + y = 8: 2x + (x - 1) = 8 → 3x - 1 = 8 → 3x = 9 → x = 3. Then y = 3 - 1 = 2.": "",
  "Solve: x + 3y = 11 and x = y + 3.": "",
  "x = 8, y = 1": "",
  "x = 3, y = 0": "",
  "x = 5, y = 2": "",
  "x = 6, y = 3": "",
  "Substitute x = y + 3 into x + 3y = 11: (y + 3) + 3y = 11 → 4y + 3 = 11 → 4y = 8 → y = 2. Then x = 2 + 3 = 5.": "",
  "Solve: y = 4x and 3x + y = 14.": "",
  "x = 3, y = 12": "",
  "x = 2, y = 8": "",
  "x = 4, y = 16": "",
  "Substitute y = 4x into 3x + y = 14: 3x + 4x = 14 → 7x = 14 → x = 2. Then y = 4(2) = 8.": "",
  "Solve: x - y = 3 and 2x + 3y = 16.": "",
  "x = 7, y = 4": "",
  "From the first equation: x = y + 3. Substitute into 2(y + 3) + 3y = 16 → 2y + 6 + 3y = 16 → 5y = 10 → y = 2. Then x = 2 + 3 = 5.": "",
  "Solve: 4x - y = 5 and y = 2x + 1.": "",
  "x = 1, y = 3": "",
  "x = 4, y = 9": "",
  "x = 2, y = 5": "",
  "Substitute y = 2x + 1 into 4x - y = 5: 4x - (2x + 1) = 5 → 2x - 1 = 5 → 2x = 6 → x = 3. Then y = 2(3) + 1 = 7.": "",
  "What is the substitution method for solving systems of equations?": "",
  "Graphing both equations and finding the intersection": "",
  "Solving one equation for one variable and replacing that variable in the other equation": "",
  "Multiplying both equations by the same constant": "",
  "Adding the two equations together": "",
  "The substitution method involves isolating one variable in one equation and then replacing (substituting) that expression into the other equation, creating a single-variable equation that can be solved directly.": "",
  "What does 'isolate a variable' mean?": "",
  "Substitute a number for the variable": "",
  "Set the variable equal to zero": "",
  "Rewrite the equation so one variable is alone on one side": "",
  "Remove the variable from the equation": "",
  "Isolating a variable means rearranging an equation so that the chosen variable appears by itself on one side of the equals sign. For example, solving x + y = 5 for x gives x = 5 - y.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'substitute' in algebra?": "",
  "To eliminate a variable by adding equations": "",
  "To graph an equation": "",
  "To replace a variable or expression with an equivalent value or expression": "",
  "To factor an expression": "",
  "Substitution means replacing a variable with a number or an equivalent expression. In systems, if y = 3x, you substitute 3x for y in the other equation.": "",
  "What is a 'solution to a system' of equations?": "",
  "The slope of the lines": "",
  "Any ordered pair that satisfies the first equation": "",
  "An ordered pair that satisfies all equations in the system simultaneously": "",
  "The y-intercept of any equation in the system": "",
  "A solution to a system is an ordered pair (x, y) that makes every equation in the system true when the values are substituted in. It represents the point where all equations intersect.": "",
  "When is the substitution method most convenient to use?": "",
  "When the coefficients of one variable are opposites": "",
  "When you need an approximate answer": "",
  "When one equation is already solved for a variable or can be easily solved for one": "",
  "When both equations are in standard form with large coefficients": "",
  "Substitution is most efficient when one equation is already solved for a variable (like y = 3x + 2) or when a variable has a coefficient of 1 or -1, making it easy to isolate.": "",
  "What does 'back-substitution' mean?": "",
  "Plugging the found value back into an equation to find the other variable": "",
  "Substituting in reverse order": "",
  "Checking if the answer is correct by graphing": "",
  "Undoing a substitution step": "",
  "Back-substitution is the step where, after finding one variable's value, you plug it back into one of the original equations to find the remaining variable. It completes the solution process.": "",
  "What is an ordered pair?": "",
  "Two numbers listed in a specific order, written as (x, y)": "",
  "Any two numbers added together": "",
  "The slope and y-intercept of a line": "",
  "Two equations solved simultaneously": "",
  "An ordered pair (x, y) represents a point in the coordinate plane where x is the horizontal position and y is the vertical position. The order matters — (2, 3) is different from (3, 2).": "",
  "What does 'equivalent equations' mean?": "",
  "Equations that have the same solution set": "",
  "Equations with the same slope": "",
  "Equations that are always true": "",
  "Equations that look the same": "",
  "Equivalent equations have exactly the same set of solutions. For example, 2x = 6 and x = 3 are equivalent because both have the single solution x = 3.": "",
  "What does 'verify a solution' mean in the context of systems?": "",
  "Graph the solution": "",
  "Substitute the solution into all original equations to confirm they are true": "",
  "Solve the system again using a different method": "",
  "Round the answer to the nearest integer": "",
  "Verifying a solution means plugging the values back into each original equation to make sure both sides are equal. This confirms the answer is correct and no arithmetic errors were made.": "",
  "What is a 'linear expression'?": "",
  "An expression with a radical": "",
  "An expression with no variables": "",
  "An expression where the variable has degree one (no exponents greater than 1)": "",
  "An expression containing a squared variable": "",
  "A linear expression is one where variables appear only to the first power — like 3x + 2 or 5y - 1. There are no squared terms, square roots, or other nonlinear operations on the variables.": "",
  "A parking garage charges $3 for the first hour and $2 for each additional hour. If the total charge is C = 2h + 1 (where h is total hours), and a second garage charges C = 3h - 2, after how many hours do both garages charge the same amount?": "",
  "3 hours": "",
  "5 hours": "",
  "4 hours": "",
  "2 hours": "",
  "Set 2h + 1 = 3h - 2: 1 + 2 = 3h - 2h → h = 3. After 3 hours both charge $7.": "",
  "A tutoring center offers Plan A at $20/session and Plan B at $15/session plus a $30 registration fee. If a student attends s sessions, when do both plans cost the same?": "",
  "10 sessions": "",
  "4 sessions": "",
  "6 sessions": "",
  "8 sessions": "",
  "Plan A: C = 20s. Plan B: C = 15s + 30. Set equal: 20s = 15s + 30 → 5s = 30 → s = 6 sessions. Both cost $120.": "",
  "A pet store sells fish for $2 each and hamsters for $8 each. Maria buys 7 pets for $26. How many fish did she buy?": "",
  "5": "",
  "6": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "Let f = fish, h = hamsters. f + h = 7 and 2f + 8h = 26. From the first: h = 7 - f. Substitute: 2f + 8(7 - f) = 26 → 2f + 56 - 8f = 26 → -6f = -30 → f = 5.": "",
  "A baker uses 2 cups of flour per loaf of bread and 3 cups per batch of cookies. She uses 24 cups total and makes 10 items. How many batches of cookies did she make?": "",
  "Let b = loaves, c = cookie batches. b + c = 10 and 2b + 3c = 24. From the first: b = 10 - c. Substitute: 2(10 - c) + 3c = 24 → 20 - 2c + 3c = 24 → c = 4.": "",
  "Two cell phone plans are being compared. Plan X charges $40/month plus $0.10/text, and Plan Y charges $25/month plus $0.25/text. For how many texts per month are they equal?": "",
  "150 texts": "",
  "75 texts": "",
  "100 texts": "",
  "50 texts": "",
  "Set 40 + 0.10t = 25 + 0.25t: 15 = 0.15t → t = 100 texts. Both plans cost $50 at 100 texts.": "",
  "A student scores y = 2x + 60 on a math test and y = -x + 90 on a science test, where x is hours of study. For how many hours of study will the scores be equal?": "",
  "15 hours": "",
  "10 hours": "",
  "8 hours": "",
  "Set 2x + 60 = -x + 90: 3x = 30 → x = 10. Both scores equal 80 at 10 hours of study.": "",
  "A juice stand mixes apple juice at $3/liter with grape juice at $5/liter to make 8 liters of a blend costing $3.50/liter. How many liters of apple juice are used?": "",
  "4 liters": "",
  "6 liters": "",
  "5 liters": "",
  "3 liters": "",
  "Let a = apple, g = grape. a + g = 8 and 3a + 5g = 28 (since 8 × 3.50 = 28). Substitute g = 8 - a: 3a + 5(8 - a) = 28 → 3a + 40 - 5a = 28 → -2a = -12 → a = 6.": "",
  "A rental company offers trucks for $30/day plus $0.20/mile and vans for $45/day plus $0.10/mile. After how many miles in one day does the truck cost the same as the van?": "",
  "100 miles": "",
  "150 miles": "",
  "200 miles": "",
  "75 miles": "",
  "Set 30 + 0.20m = 45 + 0.10m: 0.10m = 15 → m = 150 miles. At 150 miles both cost $60.": "",
  "A theater group sold 120 tickets. Adult tickets cost $8 and student tickets cost $5. Total revenue was $780. Using substitution, find how many student tickets were sold.": "",
  "40": "",
  "80": "",
  "60": "",
  "50": "",
  "Let a = adult, s = student. a + s = 120, so a = 120 - s. Substitute: 8(120 - s) + 5s = 780 → 960 - 3s = 780 → -3s = -180 → s = 60.": "",
  "An electrician charges a $50 call-out fee plus $35/hour. A plumber charges a $20 call-out fee plus $45/hour. After how many hours will they charge the same total?": "",
  "Set 50 + 35h = 20 + 45h: 30 = 10h → h = 3. Both charge $155 after 3 hours.": ""
